Q1: Are there any disparities in arrest rates based on race?

arrests_by_race <- NC_stops %>%
group_by(subject_race) %>%
  filter(subject_race %in% c("asian/pacific islander","black","white","hispanic")) %>%
  summarize(arrest_rate=mean(outcome=="arrest",na.rm=TRUE))

arrests_by_race
## # A tibble: 4  2
##   subject_race           arrest_rate
##   <chr>                        <dbl>
## 1 asian/pacific islander      0.0157
## 2 black                       0.0353
## 3 hispanic                    0.0526
## 4 white                       0.0219
ggplot(arrests_by_race, aes(x = subject_race, y = arrest_rate)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = "steelblue") +
  labs(title = "Arrest Rates by Race",
       x = "Race",
       y = "Arrest Rate") +
  theme_minimal()

Q2: Are there differences in outcomes for the different reasons for getting stopped?

filtered_outcomes <- NC_stops %>%
  select('reason_for_stop', 'outcome')

filtered_outcomes
## # A tibble: 3,054,884  2
##    reason_for_stop               outcome 
##    <chr>                         <chr>   
##  1 Safe Movement Violation       warning 
##  2 Vehicle Regulatory Violation  citation
##  3 Vehicle Equipment Violation   citation
##  4 Vehicle Regulatory Violation  citation
##  5 Safe Movement Violation       warning 
##  6 Other Motor Vehicle Violation warning 
##  7 Vehicle Regulatory Violation  citation
##  8 Stop Light/Sign Violation     warning 
##  9 Stop Light/Sign Violation     warning 
## 10 Stop Light/Sign Violation     warning 
## #  3,054,874 more rows
result <- filtered_outcomes %>%
  group_by(reason_for_stop, outcome) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  group_by(reason_for_stop) %>%
  mutate(proportion = count / sum(count))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'reason_for_stop'. You can override using
## the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(result, aes(x = reason_for_stop, y = proportion, fill = outcome)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Outcomes by Reason for Stop",
       x = "Reason for Stop",
       y = "Proportion") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Q2: After getting stopped, what identifiers (race/gender) are most likely to get let off with just a warning?

StopsNA = NC_stops[!is.na(NC_stops$subject_race),]
StopsNA = StopsNA[!is.na(StopsNA$subject_sex),]
pergroup = matrix(NA, nrow = length(unique(StopsNA$subject_sex)), ncol = length(unique(StopsNA$subject_race)))
unique_race = unique(NC_stops$subject_race )
unique_sex = unique(NC_stops$subject_sex )
for(j in unique(StopsNA$subject_sex)){                    
  for(k in unique(StopsNA$subject_race)){ 
    rs = filter(StopsNA, subject_race==k, subject_sex == j)
    warning = filter(rs, outcome == "warning")
    percent = nrow(warning) / nrow(rs)
    pergroup[which(unique(StopsNA$subject_sex)==j), which(unique(StopsNA$subject_race)==k)] <- percent
  }} 
colnames(pergroup) <- c( "black", "white", "hispanic", "asian/pacific islander", "unknown", "other")
rownames(pergroup) <- c("female", "male")
pergroup

Q1: Do certain age groups get stopped for specific reasons more than others? (i.e.older demographic having more stop light violations)

##groups by the age and reason for stops
age_reason_counts <- NC_stops %>%
  group_by(subject_age, reason_for_stop) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  ungroup()
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subject_age'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
##creates a heatmap that displays how often an age group is stopped for each reason
ggplot(age_reason_counts, aes(x = subject_age, y = reason_for_stop, fill = count)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") +
  labs(
    x = "Age Group",
    y = "Reason for Stop",
    fill = "Count"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Q2:How have arrest rates changed since 2001?

## calculates arrest rates by year
arrest_rates <- NC_stops %>%
  mutate(year = lubridate::year(date)) %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(
    total_stops = n(),
    total_arrests = sum(arrest_made == "TRUE"),
    arrest_rate = total_arrests / total_stops
  ) %>%
  ungroup()
##Returns a lineplot of arrest rates by year
ggplot(arrest_rates, aes(x = year, y = arrest_rate)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(
    x = "Year",
    y = "Arrest Rate",
    title = "Arrest Rate Trends Since 2001"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

Q1: What is the likelihood of finding contraband after a search is done?

filtered_data <- NC_stops %>% filter(search_conducted == TRUE)
search_and_contraband_counts <- table(filtered_data$search_conducted, filtered_data$contraband_found)
search_and_contraband_counts_df <- as.data.frame(search_and_contraband_counts)
colnames(search_and_contraband_counts_df) <- c("Search_Conducted", "No_Contraband", "Contraband_Found")
search_and_contraband_counts_df$Likelihood_Contraband_Found <- 
  search_and_contraband_counts_df$Contraband_Found / 
  (search_and_contraband_counts_df$Contraband_Found + search_and_contraband_counts_df$No_Contraband)
## Warning in Ops.factor(search_and_contraband_counts_df$Contraband_Found, : '+'
## not meaningful for factors
search_and_contraband_counts_df
##   Search_Conducted No_Contraband Contraband_Found Likelihood_Contraband_Found
## 1             TRUE         FALSE           120101                          NA
## 2             TRUE          TRUE            38007                          NA
data <- data.frame(
  Search_Conducted = c("TRUE", "TRUE"),
  Contraband_Found = c("FALSE", "TRUE"),
  Frequency = c(120101, 38007)
)
ggplot(data, aes(x = Search_Conducted, y = Frequency, fill = Contraband_Found)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Search Conducted", y = "Frequency", title = "Relationship Between Search Conducted and Contraband Found") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("FALSE" = "blue", "TRUE" = "red")) +
  theme_minimal()

Q2: Are there any disparities among each police department and their arrest rates?

department_arrest_rates <- NC_stops %>%
  group_by(department_name) %>%
  summarize(
    total_stops = n(),
    arrest_count = sum(arrest_made == "TRUE"),
    arrest_prop = mean(arrest_made == "TRUE")
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(arrest_prop))
department_arrest_rates

  labs(x = "Department Name", y = "Arrest Proportion", title = "Arrest Proportions by Police Department") +

Q2: What combination of race, sex and age factors result in the highest arrest rates? And the lowest?

filtered_search$age_group <- cut(filtered_search$subject_age, breaks = seq(10, 120, by = 5), include.lowest = TRUE, right = FALSE)

cleaned_data <- filtered_search %>% 
  filter(!subject_race %in% c("unknown", "other", NA)) %>%
  filter(!subject_age %in% c(NA))

summary_df <- cleaned_data %>%
  group_by(subject_race, subject_sex, age_group) %>%
  summarise(Total_Stops = n(),
            Arrests_Made = sum(arrest_made, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(Arrest_Rate = Arrests_Made / Total_Stops * 100)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subject_race', 'subject_sex'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.
relevant_data <- summary_df %>% 
  filter(Total_Stops >= 1000)

top_5_highest_arrest_rates <- relevant_data %>% 
  arrange(desc(Arrest_Rate)) %>%
  head(5)

top_5_lowest_arrest_rates <- relevant_data %>% 
  arrange(Arrest_Rate) %>%
  head(5)

list(top_5_highest_arrest_rates = top_5_highest_arrest_rates, top_5_lowest_arrest_rates = top_5_lowest_arrest_rates)

Summary

GIVE A 2 PARAGRAPH SUMMARY.

PARAGRAPH 1 SHOULD DESCRIBE WHAT YOU LEARNED ABOUT YOUR DATA FROM INVESTIGATING THE INITIAL QUESTIONS. DID YOU FIND ANYTHING UNUSUAL IN YOUR DATA? DID ANYTHING SURPRISE YOU? WHICH OF THE INITIAL QUESTIONS WERE HELPFUL IN LEADING YOU TO MORE QUESTIONS?

DESCRIBE THE TABLES/FIGURES YOU USED TO EXPLORE ANSWERS TO THESE FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS? WHAT DID YOU LEARN FROM THE TABLES/FIGURES REGARDING THE FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS YOU PROPOSED?

In our analysis of the data, we investigated several key questions and gained valuable insights into law enforcement activities in the biggest cities in North Carolina. After finding significant disparities in arrest rates between males and females, we looked into the underlying causes of these gender-based differences in the types of arrests. Notably, we discovered that black people were more likely than other racial groups to be searched after a stop, although Hispanic people had the greatest rates of arrests of any race. We looked further into both extremes of arrest rates across various demographic categories as a result of this finding. Our data analysis also revealed an interesting association between search conducted and contraband found. Less than 25% of searches resulted in the discovery of contraband, which is surprising. This observation made us wonder if there were racial disparities in the likelihood of discovering contraband following a search. In addition, we discovered an unusual trend while looking at the quantity of stops that happen every month. Based on the data, it was found that the most stops happened at the start of the year, and the least number happened at the end. This unusual pattern raised questions about possible causes of these variations, such as quotas or other outside influences on officers behavior. It also prompted us to explore how, over the course of the year, the frequency of stops for different racial groups changed. Answering our initial questions only led to us having further questions about the dataset, and we realized how much additional information we could glean from it. For example, we initially asked if there were disparities in traffic stops among the sexes. Then for our follow-up question, we asked if there were differences in the type of offenses for which men and women who were arrested were stopped for. This question took the basis of our original one, and investigates further. To explore the first follow-up question, we created a bar chart comparing the reasons for stops, the proportion of these stops that result in arrests, and the disparities between the sexes regarding this issue. For the second follow-up question, we created a table that grouped the age of the subjects in five year groups, and then found the different combinations of sex, group, and race that have the highest percentage of arrests, and the combinations that have the lowest. From the bar chart created for the first follow-up question, we were able to see a fascinating disparity between the reasons for stops, and it seems that for almost every variable, men are far more likely to be stopped, aside from two notable exceptions - Driving While Impaired, and Vehicle Regulatory Violation, in which women have a significantly higher proportion. Through examining our second question, and the table it created, we were able to better understand what factors made a person more likely to be arrested after being stopped during the years 2001 through 2015. For example, younger men were far more likely to be arrested, while older women were far less likely to be arrested.
